6247.content:
title: Evacuation from Vovchansk and Lipetsk communities 10-31 May 2024 
 content: SUMMARY
On May 10th 2024 the mass evacuation from Vovchansk and Lipetsk communities began.
From the first day, the Relief Coordination Centre has been involved in the administration, processes setup and coordination of organizations involved both in the evacuation missions and the work at the transit point in Kharkiv city.
The evacuation hotline of the Relief Coordination Centre accepted applications for evacuation and distributed them among the volunteer evacuation crews of local charitable organizations.
At the end of each evacuation mission, people were brought to the transit point in a centralized manner, allowing to keep correct statistics on the movement of people from each settlement. Thanks to this, each evacuated person could receive all the necessary assistance and immediately get settled in collective centers for IDPs. As of May 31st, more than 52 charitable organizations have been involved in the work at the transit point, providing assistance in various areas, including:
food items;
hygiene kits;
NFIs;
cash assistance;
MHPSS;
medical aid;
legal aid;
aid to animals;
hot meals.
A system of registration of each person present at the transit point, rules of conduct at the location for evacuees, charitable organizations and journalists have been developed. Each person involved in the work of the transit point had their own clearly outlined area of responsibility in all the overall operation.

9278.content:
title: Ukraine Education Cluster - Kharkivska oblast (May - July 2024) 
 content: Key Response Activities Objective:
In the context of displacement and escalating hostilities, education activities aim to restore routine and a sense of normalcy for affected children, with protection mainstreamed in the response. Education Cluster activities in Kharkivska oblast aim at ensuring protecting children’s wellbeing in the face of displacement, whilst ensuring children’s right to education is protected amid the disruptions caused by the recent escalation of hostilities. Namely, key response activities support access to wellbeing and learning in safe spaces, learning for school-age children on the move (evacuees); access to learning and wellbeing activities for children in safe spaces in Kharkiv city and oblast whose online education might be disrupted by increased missile attacks and damages to civil infrastructure (electricity and internet cuts); access to offline learning and wellbeing activities for both displaced and host community children to ensure they keep up with formal schooling and minimize learning losses after their learning was disrupted; support for teachers who might be themselves affected by escalations (displaced) and face increased workload and challenges in supporting their students.
Activities:
• Provision of MHPSS for children (including social-emotional learning and informal education support)
• Distribution of learning kits and electronic devices for learning;
• Establishment of safe spaces for children to play, and receive wellbeing and learning support ( (Temporary Learning Spaces/Digital Learning Centers);
• Catch up learning support services for children to regain access to formal learning;
• Wellbeing support services for teachers.
